http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Long before it was a cable hub, Katong was a center of private wealth in British Malaya. Colonial elites established giant mansions, coconut plantations, and weekend villas along the waterfront in this East Singapore district from the early nineteenth century onwards. Though some of these structures have been preserved and restored, often painted bright colors, the still-affluent neighborhood has also seen some major physical transformations. The beach where you emerge from the APCN-2 network didn’t even exist before the 1970s. It was created as part of a massive land-reclamation project designed to add more space for housing on the island. Modern apartment towers and Singapore’s largest park now occupy the expanded coastal area. Soon after the artificial beach was completed, a telephone cable arrived from Hong Kong, followed by connections to regional fiber-optic networks in the 1990s and early 2000s.

Forming the southern edge of Tokyo Bay, the Izu Peninsula received its first domestic underwater cables in the 1970s. In the 1990s, international systems joined Miura to the rest of Asia, Europe, and the U.S., echoing a long history of maritime connections. In 1600, English navigator William Adams arrived in Japan and became a government advisor on shipbuilding and foreign affairs. Renamed “the pilot of Miura,” Adams settled near present-day Yokosuka in eastern Miura, now a major Japanese and U.S. naval base. More than four hundred years later, Minoru Saito became the oldest person to sail non-stop around the world at age 71, beginning and ending in Miura. The 234-day solo journey was his seventh circumnavigation.

The optical underwater Asia-Pacific Cable (APC) was completed in 1993 and linked Japan, Taiwan, Malaysia, and Singapore until its decommissioning in 2006. Run by an international consortium, the APC promised to create a “fiber backbone for the region’s burgeoning telecommunications infrastructure,” explains an industry newsletter from 1991.

As you approach Colombo, Ceylon (present-day Sri Lanka) in 1903, your travel guide tells you: “its appearance is extremely picturesque: a fine undulating country, well wooded to the water’s edge and fringed by cocoa-nut trees; lofty verdant ranges tower in the distance, covered with groves of talipat and other palms.” Centrally positioned in the Indian Ocean, Colombo was a key trade port long before the colonial era. In the early 1500s, the Portuguese established a fort and trading post to capitalize on the island’s abundant cinnamon crops. After a brief Dutch occupation, Colombo was ceded to the British and became the capital of British Ceylon. To facilitate faster communication to London, a submarine cable was brought to the island via the Middle East in 1913, connecting to a new Central Telegraph Office in a three-story wood building near the harbor. Messages could now travel between the two cities in as little as thirty minutes, a savings of nearly four hours compared to older land-based routes through India. Today, messages transit in only milliseconds from five cable systems that land in the Colombo area.

SeaMeWe-2, laid in 1994, was one of the first optical fiber systems in Southeast Asia and it set records for cable length. Its technical advances achieved capacities 15 times that of its coaxial predecessor SeaMeWe-1. However, the complexities and costs of the project meant that fewer countries were ultimately linked to the network.

You arrive at a cable station fit for a king. Constructed for the landing of a new fiber-optic network, one cable industry leader recalls that the Tungku station was “built as a palace” so that it could be inaugurated by the Sultan of Brunei. In the following years, the massive station would become a hub of links to Singapore, Malaysia, and the Philippines, followed by connections reaching as far as the U.S. and Western Europe. When a link to the Asia-America Gateway in 2009 created an oversupply of bandwidth, the Brunei government sold it to international carriers in order to finance new cable landings. Located a few miles north of the capital, the station is at once remote and central, surrounded by trees but also a highway exchange and the campuses of both the University of Brunei and an international boarding school. Across the street, a fifteen-story glass office tower (and the second tallest building in the country) contains the headquarters of local telecom provider DataStream Technology Group. When cables first arrived on nearby Tungku Beach in the 1990s, illegal sand mining had caused severe erosion. But the jagged shoreline has been restored and is now a popular place for watching sunsets.

Landing at one of two designated sites on the northern and southern coasts of Changi, you make your way inland to a cluster of stations that form East Singapore’s primary cable hub. Today, the area is known for its major international airport complex, which includes a cactus garden, butterfly habitat, and what will soon be the world’s largest indoor waterfall. But this cutting-edge cable and aviation crossroads has a dark history. The British established a military base at Changi in the early 1900s when the peninsula was still mostly swampland and forests of tall “chengei” trees. During its occupation of Singapore in World War II, Japan used the compound to imprison thousands of captured Allied soldiers. (The prison was rebuilt in the 1990s and now has a death-row detention center.) Even the northern beaches where cables come ashore, a popular spot for picnics and watersports, were the setting for a brutal 1942 massacre of Chinese Singaporeans thought to be anti-Japanese.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/title.value: ASEAN Optical Fibre Submarine Cable Network (AOFSCN)

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In the early 1990s, the member countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, or ASEAN, banded together to set up this cable system, nicknamed "Asia's Fiber Glove" by one news report. It stretched from Brunei to Singapore, north to Malaysia, and then onward to Thailand and the Philippines. When the APCN cable was laid, this created a redundant loop, ensuring traffic would continue even in the case of a cable break.

No one is allowed past the gate to Cape D’Aguilar, except those with permission. At the southeast edge of Hong Kong Island, the cape’s high hills formed a perfect location for a radio station, once Hong Kong’s major high-frequency transmission center. From here, signals broadcast past the nearby mountains and out onto the ocean, where fishermen benefit from regular weather updates. When an old building nearby was retrofitted as a cable landing station, these radio signals became a problem. The high-powered wireless threatened to damage the building’s electronics equipment. The station had to be completely protected and insulation was placed throughout its interior. As a result, the cable station is a completely wireless-free zone: not even mobile phones will work inside.
The Japanese Military connected Nagasaki and Tsingtau in 1914.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: On AtlanticCable.com, many landings indicated by "Mogi, Nagasaki-ken, Japan"

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Like many port cities in Asia, Nagasaki was “discovered” by imperial powers – in this case, the Portuguese – and developed for trade. In the nineteenth century, Nagasaki became a busy transit point, with a vibrant ship-building industry, an anchorage site for the Japanese navy, and a telegraph cable landing point. Three years after its first submarine telegraph cable was landed in 1871, the telegraph company established a headquarters here, in a large two-story office building abutting the harbor. Within a few years, Japan would build up its internal landlines, and the country would be connected to the rest of the world via Nagasaki. The importance of this station was clear to Japan and its enemies. Described as “clutching the aeortic artery of international communications in Japan,” Nagasaki, as a hub and military harbor, was also a target. The cable to Vladivostok was taken out of service during the Russo-Japanese War, but the city remained undamaged. During World War II, however, Nagasaki was hit with the atomic bomb, the second and last to ever be deployed, killing several hundred thousand people. After the Japanese surrender, the city would slowly rebuild. Old communications lines were taken out of service, and new coaxial cables laid in their place.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: When China began to struggle against imperialism in the late 1800s, Qingdao was an important node of resistance. The Boxers, an anti-imperialist, proto-nationalist Chinese movement, had a strong presence in area, and in 1897, the Chinese government began building up a military base here to protect against foreign invasion. Shortly thereafter, German troops seized and occupied this fort. After a year of fighting, China conceded the area to Germany, who re-named the city Tsingtau, a French transliteration of the original name. This small Chinese fishing village was transformed into a German administrative and economic center, with tall three-story stone buildings, wide streets, electricity, and a navy base. At the turn of the century, two telegraph cables were landed, one connecting to Tschifu and one to Shanghai. Today, two major cable systems continue to land at Qingdao, linking the city to Korea and across the sea to California.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Waves crash up against a thick seawall that spans the coast of Toucheng. Much of the shore here in northeast Taiwan is comprised of sand rock, eroded by ocean waves and monsoon winds. Some locals think these spectacular rock formations resemble tofu. Yet the erosion here is not entirely natural. The presence of manmade structures on 56% of Taiwan’s coast, this seawall included, has sped up the disappearance of its beaches. These structures interrupt the flow of sand, causing it to accumulate on one side and to quickly erode on the other. The nearby Toucheng beach, which once stretched for two kilometers, is now severely diminished, and the coast has retreated up to 100 meters inland. This seawall keeps the shoreline intact for both waves and cable stations, but provides an additional challenge for cable laying. Companies have to bore a hole through the thick walls in order to thread their networks through.

Popular with surfers and backpackers, the small fishing village of Cherating lies approximately twenty miles north of Kuantan on the central east coast of Malaysia. Every spring and summer, leatherback sea turtles swim through the calm waters and lay their eggs on broad sand beaches lined with Casuarina trees. These same environmental conditions are well suited to underwater cable landings: sand is an accommodating medium for cable burial and there are no strong ocean currents to shift or expose cables once in place. Although cables have connected here since the 1980s, the current station was built as part of Telekom Malaysia’s investment in the APCN-2 system of the early 2000s. A single-story complex with pitched roofs set back from the road and surrounded by a security fence, the Cherating cable station is relatively unassuming. But a large communications tower, visible for miles, marks the site as a hub for signal traffic.

From a mostly undeveloped beach several miles north of Miyazaki, you follow a dirt path inland until it opens onto a single-lane road. In the distance, a ringed communications tower is visible above the treetops. Homing in on this beacon, you reach a windowless building surrounded on all sides by a barbed-wire fence. Three majestic palm trees and a plaque bearing the logo of Japanese telecom company KDDI mark the entrance, while farmland and greenhouses occupy the surrounding plots. In 1977, the first telephone cable arrived from Okinawa, where a trans-Pacific link to the U.S. had recently been completed. Optical cables followed in the 1990s, but more recent connections have overlooked Miyazaki in favor of the cluster of hubs along the east coast of Honshu Island.

North of the original telegraph termination point at Weltevreden lies Jakarta’s post-independence cable hub. The area’s swamplands were once the home to the Dutch Fort Zouteland (“saline land”), and during the Japanese occupation of Jakarta during World War II, Ancol was the site of mass executions and burials. In films of the 60s and 70s, Ancol was portrayed as a mysterious and ghostly place. After Indonesia gained independence, the country’s founding President envisioned the transformation of Jakarta into a great international city, and coastal Ancol as a space for recreation, a “showcase of the nation.” His dreams were not recognized for decades, and even then, they came at a price. Developers dredged the nearby coast, destroying a beach that had made it accessible to Indonesia’s underclass, and converted the marshland for recreation facilities. Today, the theme park Ancol Dreamland, Sea World of Indonesia, resort hotels, and beaches are all accessible only with a fee.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Established in 1997, the Asia-Pacific Cable Network (APCN) spans more than 7,400 miles and connects Japan, Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong, the Philippines, Indonesia, Singapore, Malaysia, and Thailand. A telecom consortium (including AT&T, Alcatel-Lucent, and KDD Submarine Cable Systems) owns this regional trunk-and-branch network.
